dren."]},{"name":"Wynn","meanings":["English: from a Middle English survival of the Old English word <i>wine</i> ‘friend’. There was also an Old English personal name <i>Wine</i>, derived from this word, which may have given rise to the surname. It is supported by the variety of surnames that evidently originated in patronymic or diminutive forms of this name, such as   Winson  .","Welsh: from <i>gwyn</i> ‘fair, white’, also used as a personal name. See also   Gwin  ."]},{"name":"Winnett","meanings":["English (Worcestershire and Warwickshire): perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Winet</i>, a possible pet form of Old English <i>Wine</i> (see   Winn  )."]}]},{"name":"Gertraut","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>gēr</i>, <i>gār</i> ‘spear’ + <i>þrūþ</i> ‘strength’; the name of two famous 13th-century nuns of the Cistercian Abbey of Helfta near Eisleben, whose spiritual writings had a great influence."],"variants":[{"name":"Gertraud","meanings":["from <i>gēr</i>, <i>gār</i> ‘spear’ + <i>þrūþ</i> ‘strength’; the name of two famous 13th-century nuns of the Cistercian Abbey of Helfta near Eisleben, whose spiritual writings had a great influence."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gertraut Winn was born in 1630, in Prussia as the daughter of Johannes Winn. She married George Willhelm Koll about 1645, in Rengsdorf, Neuwied, Rhineland, Prussia. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1722, in Melsbach, Neuwied, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany, at the age of 92."},"et":{"1630–1722":"1630–1722","1619–Male":"1619–Surnud","1650–1715":"1650–1715","1610–Male":"1610–Surnud","1722":"1722","1610":"1610","1630":"1630","Abt 1650":"1650","26 Jun 1704":"26. juuni 1704","about 1645":"umbes 1645","1650":"1650","1619":"1619","1715":"1715","Rengsdorf, , Rheinland-Pfalz, Germany":"Rengsdorf, Landkreis Neuwied, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksamaa","Nierstein, Mainz-Bingen, Rheinland-Pfalz, G